N2  -  Objectives Most clinicians have not received formal teacher training but are required to teach on the job hence faculty development (FD), staff development, training the trainers courses to prepare clinical educators for their role in teaching has increasingly become more important. The investment in such training courses is predicated on the belief that it enhances the effectiveness of teaching but evidence is limited. The aim of this study was to carry out an in‐depth exploration of FD for clinical educators (O & G and non‐O & G) and evaluate its effectiveness using the realist framework with its principle of explanatory causation to find out what works for who in FD, in what context, and why. Methods A detailed literature review was carried out, informing the development of realist hypotheses in the form of contexts + mechanisms = outcomes (CMO) realist framework. Contexts are the individual, interpersonal, institutional and infrastructural factors that influence programme efficiency. Mechanisms describe what it is about interventions (programmes / courses) that make them work while outcomes are the consequences of the intervention. Data to support, modify, or challenge the hypotheses were collected in two phases. Phase I was observation and interviews of two cohorts of clinical teachers attending a FD course followed by interviews of 12 teachers 6 months later. Phase II was interviews of course developers and clinical teachers in eight UK regions (deaneries). Qualitative data were analysed by categorising and connecting strategies followed by summarising the relevant data under each hypothesis to check if the hypothesis was supported, modified or refuted. Results Data from both phases supported four realist theories based on the framework of contexts + mechanisms = outcomes. Theory 1 Engagement Participatory approach / reflective practice in FD + Engagement = Increased confidence in teaching. Theory 2 Motivation Needs assessment of educators / FD relevance + Motivation to learn = Improved competence. Theory 3 Positive perception FD in a supportive setting / access to programmes + Positive perception of the value of teaching = Credibility as a teacher. Theory 4 Professionalization Demand to standardise teaching / accreditation + professionalization of teaching = Career progression / improved recognition. Conclusions Four realist theories of FD illuminated the effectiveness of FD both in the short and long term. Teaching can no longer be left to chance or aptitude hence these are important findings for all stakeholders involved in the teaching and training of doctors including O&G.
