N2  -  Background and Objectives: It is critical that junior faculty have access to resources that can help develop their skills as medical educators. KeyLIME (Key Literature in Medical Education) is a weekly podcast for medical educators that discusses medical education literature in a journal‐club format but is targeted to more senior educators. Its advanced nature limits its potential impact on junior faculty who may have difficulty understanding the material discussed. Junior faculty are therefore left without asynchronous faculty development resources to increase their medical education knowledge. This study objectively explores whether reading a supplementary blog post, KeyLEMON (Key Literature in Education and Medicine Online for Novices), with background information about the featured journal club article prior to listening to a KeyLIME episode improves understanding and knowledge retention of the KeyLIME episode. This study will objectively explore the value of asynchronous resources such as blogs and will address a void created by the lack of asynchronous resources for junior faculty. Methods: This is an experimental, randomized trial of junior faculty members, defined as assistant/associate program directors and medical education fellows, in North America. Participants were randomized as to whether they were provided with the KeyLEMON blog post. All participants then listened to the associated KeyLIME podcast episode and completed an assessment quiz. The quiz was content validated and piloted prior to administration. Raw total score (RTS) for the quiz was calculated for each participant. Results: 172 participants enrolled from 103 institutions, 103 (60%) completed the study. There was no difference in the median number of years in current position or years since residency graduation in the blog versus no‐blog group, nor was there a difference in number of participants that hold an advanced degree between the groups. There was no difference in the median RTS between the blog (7.0, IQR 3.0) and no‐blog (6.0, IQR 3.0) groups (p=0.12). Conclusion: The addition of KeyLEMON improved knowledge acquisition from KeyLIME but was not statistically significant. This is the first study to quantitatively explore the value of asynchronous learning resources on learner knowledge acquisition. Future studies should focus on the objective value of asynchronous resources and on the lack of asynchronous resources for junior faculty.
UR  -  https://www.cochranelibrary.com/central/doi/10.1002/central/CN-02142121/full
